      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i need some help with a candidate rejection email. we had a guy named Marcus who made it all the way to the final round for a senior dev position here in austin. he was actually really good and had great technical skills, but we decided to go with someone who had a bit more experience with distributed systems. i want the email to be professional and kind since he was a strong contender, but still firm that we aren't moving forward. can you draft something for me?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I can help you draft a rejection email that's both professional and kind. Here's a possible version:\n\nDear Marcus,\n\nI wanted to personally reach out to you regarding the status of your application for the Senior Developer position at our Austin office. We were impressed by your technical skills and overall fit for the role, and I'm grateful for the time you took to interview with us. Unfortunately, after careful consideration, we've decided to move forward with another candidate whose experience with distributed systems aligns more closely with our current needs.\n\nPlease know that this decision wasn't made lightly, and we were genuinely impressed by your abilities. We appreciate the effort you put into preparing for the interview, and I'm confident that you'll find a great opportunity that aligns with your skills and interests.\n\nI'd like to offer you a reference, if you'd like, to help you in your future job search. We're always happy to sing the praises of talented candidates like yourself.\n\nBest regards,\n[Your Name]\n\nThis email aims to be kind and professional, while still conveying the message that we're not moving forward with Marcus's application. The reference offer is a nice touch, as it shows that you value his skills and are willing to support him in his future",
